## Introduction to Brute Forcing
A **brute force** attack is a method of attempting to guess a password or keys by automated probing. #BruteForce

Passwords are stored as hashes in system files.

Windows examples:
* unattend.xml
* sysprep.inf
* SAM

Linux examples:
* shadow
* shadow.bak
* password

Brute forcing works because administrators have to login. Their username are usually guessable and the passwords that people choose are not complex.

## Basic HTTP Auth Brute Forcing

### Password Attacks

1. Basic HTTP AUTH is used to authenticate the user to the HTTP server.
2. Proxy Server Authentication is used to authenticate the user to the intermediate proxy server.

Both of these use requests, resposne status codes, and response headers. The difference is in the status codes and the header names used.

Basic HTTP Auth:
* Client sends first requests without autnetication information with it first request.
* Server response sends has the WWW-Authenticate header field requesting credentials and defining how authentication has to take place.
* Server transmits the realm, a character string that tells the client who is requeting the data.
* Client use Base64 to encode the identifier and password.  The encoded string ist ransmitted to the server int he Authorization header field.

Common Password Attack Types:
* Dictionary attack
* Brute force
* Traffic interception
* Man in the Middle
* Key Logging
* Social engineering

### Brute Force Attack
A **brute force attack** works by trying all possible character combinations for a length we specify. The combinations of possible passwords increases quickly, however, so we should consider methods that increase our odds.

### Dictionary Attack
A dictionary attack #DictionaryAttack  tries to guess passwords with the help of lists. Seclists has many useful password and username lists.

![Pasted image 20230209201011.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### Default Passwords
Just what they sound like. They are often still active because peopole are lazy. It is generally better to start with a wordlist of credential pairs so that you don't have to match user to password.

### Hydra
**Hydra** is a tool for Login brute forcing that covers a wide variety of attacks and services and is relatively fast.

![Pasted image 20230209201401.png](data:image/png;base64,)

```bash
hydra -C /usr/share/seclists/Passwords/Default-Credentials/ftp-betterdefaultpasslist.txt 68.183.45.43 -s 30826  http-get /
```

### Username Brute Force
rockyou.txt is a commonly used password list that has been assembled from a variety of leaks and other places. Commonly used wodlist for usernames is names.txt

### Username/Password Attack
**Hydra** needs 3 flags if the credentials are in a single list to perform a brute force attack against a web service. 1. Credntials, 2. Tgt Host, 3. Tgt. Path.

Usernames and passwords can be on separate lists. Use -L flag for usernames wordlist and the -P flag for the passwords wordlist. We can tell hydra to stop on the first successful login using the -f flag. If we add the -i flag it tries all users on each password instead of trying all 14 million passwords on each user.

We'd like to cause as little network traffic as possible so we should start with the 10 most popular admin credentials.

### Brute Forcing Forms

Hydra has many different types of requests that can be seen using hydra -h
![Pasted image 20230209205530.png](data:image/png;base64,)
For **http** modules, we're interested in 
1. http-{head|get|post}
2. http-post-form

Basic http auth is 1, .php and .aspx are 2.

For any of these forms we use hydra \[name of form\] -U to explain the usage and requirements.

### Fail/Success String
We need to give hydra a Fail/Success string so that it can distinguish between successfully submitted creds and failed ones.

If we give a fail string, it will keep looking until it does not get the fail string. If we provide a success string it will keep looking until it gets the success string.

The string is taken from the html.  When we choose a fail string it's something unique on the login page that probably won't be on the landing page after login. 

## Determine Login Parameters
We can use a proxy or take a close look at the admin panel source code to determine parameters.

### Using your Browser
Browers development tools are a good way to capture a form's parameters. **Ctrl-Shift-E**, then after the request is made right-click and copy POST data or copy as cURL.

## Login Form attacks
A default credentials password attack:
```bash
hydra -C /opt/useful/SecLists/Passwords/Default-Credentials/ftp-betterdefaultpasslist.txt 178.35.49.134 -s 32901 http-post-form "/login.php:username=^USER^&password=^PASS^:F=<form name='login'"
```
Same attack but using the default name 'admin':
```bash

hydra -l admin -P /opt/useful/SecLists/Passwords/Leaked-Databases/rockyou.txt -f 178.35.49.134 -s 32901 http-post-form "/login.php:username=^USER^&password=^PASS^:F=<form name='login'"
```

## Custom Dictionaries

Can be made with [CUPP](https://github.com/Mebus/cupp).

Run it in interactive mode with the -i argument and it will ask you a bnch of questions about someone then generate passwords.

We can use sed and REGEX to remove passwords that don't meet particular policies, if known.
```bash
sed -ri '/^.{,7}$/dginny.txt            # remove shorter than 8
sed -ri '/[!-/:-@\[-`\{-~]+/!d' ginny.txt # remove no special chars
sed -ri '/[0-9]+/!d' ginny.txt            # remove no numbers
```

sed -ri '/^.{,7}$/d' harry.txt | sed -ri '/[!-/:-@\[-`\{-~]+/!d' | sed -ri '/[0-9]+/!d'

Once we have a custom wordlist we can put it through a mangler to mash them up and make the wordlist even larger. Many great tools do word mangling and case permutation quickly and easily, like [rsmangler](https://github.com/digininja/RSMangler) or [The Mentalist](https://github.com/sc0tfree/mentalist.git).

We can run our shortened wordlist first, then try and mangle the wordlist if necessary when we don't get a working password.

Something like [Username Anarchy](https://github.com/urbanadventurer/username-anarchy) is a good choice for generating potential usernames.

## Service Authentication Brute Forcing
Attacking a login service is easy with hydra.  Provide the appropriate lists and identify the service://SERVER_IP:PORT.  If SSH is enabled we can do a bruteforce on ssh:

```shell-session
user@computer $ hydra -L bill.txt -P william.txt -u -f ssh://178.35.49.134:22 -t 4
```

Once in, we can look for other potential attack surfaces by using:
```shell-session
user@computer~$ netstat -antp | grep -i list
```

```bash
hydra -l user -p /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -f 178.35.49.134 -s 32901 http-post-form "/admin_login.php:user=^USER^&pass=^PASS^:F=<form name='log-in'"
```
